g.text: cataloged items are a subtype of collection objects.
The catalog number of the cataloged item, including any prefix or suffix. Automatically assembled from cat_num_prefix, cat_num_integer, and cat_num_suffix.
The accession under which this cataloged item was brought into the museum.
The collecting event in which this cataloged item was collected.
The collection code for the collection within which this cataloged item is held. Autopopulated convenience field with value obtained from collection.
The type of the cataloged item, FS=fossil voucher, BI=biological preserved specimen, HO=human observation. Broadly corresponds to dwc:basisOfRecord and the Darwin Core classes.
Foreign key to the collection within which this cataloged item is held. Enforces virtual private database limitiations on collection.
The prefix portion of the catalog number, if any. Including any separator. Example "R-"
The numeric portion of the catalog number.
The suffix portion of the catalog number, if any. Including any separator. Example "-a"
Something to which a catalog number is assigned in a collection.
The collection object mentioned in the publication
The taxon name applied to the collection object in the publication.
Deprecated? Flag indicating whether this is a current citation or not. Domain: 0, 1. Almost all values are 1, Not used in UI.
The first page number in the publication on which the collection object is cited using the cited taxon name.
Primary, Secondary, or Voucher status, or other category of assertion about the cataloged item asserted by the publication.
Comments or notes about the citation.
Year that the portion of the publication containing the citation is reported to have been published.
A URI at which a resource representing the page in the publication on which the collection object is cited occurs.
Citations record the association of a taxon name with a cataloged item in a publication.
Controlled vocabulary term for publication attributes
Text guidance on use of the publication attribute
TABLE or TABLE.FIELD that provides a controlled vocabulary for this publication attribute, references a code table.
Flag indicating that the attribute applies to MCZ publications and is used in the publications.mcz.harvard.edu web presentation of publication data.
Taxonomic class into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic order into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic suborder into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic Family into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic subfamily into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic genus into which the taxon is placed, or the generic epithet for the taxon.
The subgeneric epithet for the taxon, without parenthesies.
Specific epithet part of the taxon name, if of species rank or lower.
Subspecific epithet part of the scientific name if the taxon is of rank subspecies or lower.
Flag indicating whether a taxon record is accepted by the bulkloader (1) or not (0).
The authority from which the taxon record was derived.
Automatic. Space separated list of the classification and all parts of the name of the taxon, excluding authorship.
The scientific name of the taxon.
Authorship string for the scientific name.
Taxonomic tribe into which the taxon is placed.
Rank marker to apply to the subspecific epithet if the taxon is of rank below subspecies.
Free text assertions concerning the taxon.
Taxonomic phylum into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic superfamily into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic subphylum into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic subclass into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic kingdom into which the taxon is placed.

The code of nomenclature whos rules govern the formulation of the taxon name (ICZN, ICNapf), or non-compliant if the name is in a historical form with an orthography not compliant with the current rules.
For ICNapf (botanical) names of below the species rank, the authorship string for the infraspecific part of the name.
Taxonomic infraorder into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic superorder into which the taxon is placed.
For ICNafp (botanical) names, the taxonomic rank equivalent to phylum.
For ICNafp (botanical) names, the taxonomic rank equivalent to subphylum.
Taxonomic superclass into which the taxon is placed.
Automatic. Scientific name for display in html markup, with italics where appropriate, Does not include authorship string.
Nomenclatural status for the taxon record if unavailable. Actionable, prevents italiciation of display name.
Unused. Could hold a guid for the taxon record, if the institution considers itself an authority for the taxon record.
Taxonomic infraclass into which the taxon is placed.
Taxonomic subsection into which the taxon is placed.
type of identifier used in taxonid
dwc:taxonID, a guid for the taxon record.
dwc:scientificNameID, guid for the nomenclatural act on which the taxon found in scientific_name is based.
A record concerning a taxon including the name for the taxon, its authorship, its classification, and authoritative sources of information about the taxon. Higher classifications may be
incomplete, and by design, may be inconsistent. The design intent of the flat taxonomy table is to allow different collections to support different higher classifications, e.g. a malacology
department and an invertebrate paleontology department might choose to use different higher classification schemes for molluscs. In this model, consistency in higher classification as a finding
aid is achieved through consensus and data cleanup, but not enforced by the data structure. In MCZbase, GUIDs are all external, as the MCZ does not consider itself as maintaining a
nomenclatural or taxonomic authority, just local database records that may be linked to other taxonomic or nomenclatural authorities by their guids.
